<LEADPARA>  IF the summer lineup tells us anything, it's that comedy is still king. Almost
half the movies due from now to Labor Day are either romantic comedies or
shaggy-dog lampoons. These range from "Mystery Date" and "Love Potion  9" to
such genre sendups as "Hot Shots: An Important Movie!" (Charlie Sheen in a
goof on "Top Gun") and "Suburban Commando" (Hulk Hogan's galactic warrior
subbing for you know who).;    Among the more keenly awaited rib-ticklers:
"Don't Tell Mom the Babysitter's Dead," John Hughes' "Dutch" with Ed O'Neill,
and "The Super," starring Oscar-winner Joe Pesci as a slum landlord forced to
live in his own tenement.  </LEADPARA>
<SECTION>  Weekend  </SECTION>
<HEADLINE>  SUMMERTIME MOVIE TIME
SUMMERTIME MOVIE TIME
LOOK WHO'S LAUGHING: THE STUDIOS, WITH A
CROP OF ROMANTIC COMEDIES AND LOONY LAMPOONS  </HEADLINE>
<MEMO>  Cover Stories
See also related story on page 1E in this section  </MEMO>
<TEXT>     The remaining summer movies can be subdivided according to themes, trends
and oddball permutations. There are no less than four films spawned directly
or indirectly by "Bill &amp; Ted's Excellent Adventure." They are "Bill &amp; Ted's
Bogus Journey," "Mom and Dad Save the World" (by the writers of "Bill &amp; Ted"),
"Point Break" (with Keanu Reeves, who plays Ted), and "Don't Tell Mom . . ."
(by "B&amp;T" director Steven R. Herek).;    (check) Sequels: "Scanners II," "Bill
&amp; Ted's Bogus Journey," "The Naked Gun II 1/2: The Smell of Fear," "Terminator
2: Judgment Day," "Problem Child II," "Child's Play 3," "Return to the Blue
Lagoon.";    (check) Horror and sci-fi: Disney's "Rocketeer," "Body Parts,"
"Suburban Commando," "Terminator 2," "Child's Play 3," "Mom and Daddy Save the
World.";    (check) Crime capers: "Hudson Hawk," "Point Break," and
"Mobsters," which hopes to do for the gangster opus what "Young Guns" did for
the Western.;    (check) Kidlet fodder: the animated "Rover Dangerfield," with
Rodney Dangerfield supplying the voice for a Las Vegas pooch; Disney's "Wild
Hearts Can't Be Broken," "The Rocketeer" and the "101 Dalmatians" re-release.;
   (check) Big-budget extravaganzas: Warner Bros." "Robin Hood: Prince of
Thieves" with Kevin Costner; Tri-Star's "Terminator 2," with Schwarzenegger";
Universal's "Backdraft," with Kurt Russell, William Baldwin and Robert De
Niro.;    (check) Star vehicles: "Dying Young" with Julia Roberts, "Doc
Hollywood" with Michael J. Fox, "Robin Hood" with Costner, "City Slickers"
with Billy Crystal, "Soapdish" with Sally Field and "The Butcher's Wife" with
Demi Moore.;    (check) Buddy combos: Martin Short and Danny Glover in "Pure
Luck"; the most excellent Bill and Ted in "Bogus Journey"; Richard Pryor and
Gene Wilder in "Another You"; Christian Slater and Richard Grieco in
"Mobsters"; Crystal, Bruno Kirby and Daniel Stern in "City Slickers"; Robin
Hood and his merry band; Kathleen Turner and Jay O. Sanders in "Warshawski";
Jean-Claude van Damme as twins in the Hong Kong-set "Double Impact.";
(check) Grown-up stuff: Richard Donner's "Radio Flyer," the Coen brothers'
"Barton Fink," Robert Benton's "Billy Bathgate," Randa Haines' "The Doctor,"
Spike Lee's "Jungle Fever" and Alan Parker's Dublin-set "The Commitments.";
(check) Summer's busiest actors: John Turturro in "Barton Fink," "Jungle
Fever" and "Lame Ducks," and Anthony Quinn in "Only the Lonely," "Jungle
Fever" and "Mobsters."  </TEXT>
