<CAPTION>  Photos (2); PHOTO:; Lenny Henry's talent for farce helps take 'True Identity'
into the realm of classic slapstick; PHOTO:; Director Charles Lane, left,
plays the makeup artist who gives Lenny Henry a new race in 'True Identity'  </CAPTION>
<DESCRIPT>  MOVIE; REVIEW  </DESCRIPT>
<LEADPARA>  ALL-PURPOSE scenario No. 7: Nice guy runs afoul of the Mob and must don
ridiculous disguise to give Mr. Big's thugs the slip. Everyone from Damon
Runyon to Billy Wilder (in "Some Like It Hot") has used this set-up to mine
belly laughs. And it remains a serviceable plot device -- provided you have a
decent farceur and a director who understands the mechanics of classic
slapstick.;    In director Charles Lane (the Chaplinesque "Sidewalk Stories")
and British TV star Lenny Henry, Disney has two of the most energetic and
resourceful comedy talents around. These guys have taken a plot that fairly
creaks from overuse and turned it into a sparkling comedy of errors called
"True Identity" (opening today). It's not a great movie on the order of, say,
"Tootsie," but it is lively and entertaining and scores as a refreshing
reversal on the well-meant but bogus "Black Like Me" and "Soul Man."  </LEADPARA>
<SECTION>  Eye  </SECTION>
<HEADLINE>  BLACK IN WHITE
A MOB CONTRACT FORCES A FARCICAL CHANGE IN
'IDENTITY'  </HEADLINE>
<MEMO>  MOVIES;  REVIEW  </MEMO>
<TEXT>     Better yet, it introduces us to impressionist Henry, whose devilish charm
brings to mind Harpo Marx and Richard Pryor. Henry's underworld nemesis is
played to the hilt by Frank Langella, a past master at slick villainy.;
Langella's Frank Luchino fakes his own assassination and re-emerges, with the
help of plastic surgery, as celebrated New York arts benefactor Leland Carver.
On a plane that appears fated to fall from the sky, Luchino/Carver makes a
clean breast of it to the young man in the next seat, a struggling black actor
named Miles Pope (Henry).;    Guess what? The plane doesn't crash, and a
red-faced Luchino has blown his elaborate cover. What to do? Rub out the
nobody actor, of course.;    Thank goodness Miles' best friend, Duane (Lane),
is a makeup-effects whiz. Duane not only rearranges Miles' features
(highercheekbones, less pronounced lips and nose), he changes his pigment.
Enter the new Miles, a refugee from Bensonhurst who now finds he can hail the
same midtown cab that speeds by other blacks.;    Ah, you nod -- a hip new
variation on "The Prince and the Pauper." Not quite. Though Miles eventually
finds himself ensconced in a ritzy hotel suite, he's not happy with the
surface perks his latex paint job brings.;    Shock! Surprise! We haven't
landed in another Gene Wilder-Richard Pryor "I be baaaad" comedy caper that
reinforces white myths about black inferiority.;    "I wanted to look like
Prince," Miles protests from the makeup chair. "You made me look like Wayne
Newton.";    After more twists -- and a brilliant spoof of Hitchcock's lineup
in "The Wrong Man" -- Miles is taken for his own hit man, an Italian-American
"whack" specialist imported from the West Coast.;    Now the question becomes:
Will Miles, with the help of Duane and a newfound ally (Anne-Marie Johnson),
be able to expose Luchino to the skeptical feds before Luchino and his inept
bodyguard (Andreas Katsulas) expose, and then eradicate, Miles?;    And so the
scene is set for a succession of mix-ups, masquerades and a theater climax
modeled after Hitchcock's Albert Hall sequence in "The Man Who Knew Too Much."
At various junctures, Miles appears as James Brown's younger brother Darryl, a
real estate agent, Othello and (if possible) a caricature of a Scorsese wise
guy.;    For his part, Langella fumes and swears a lot. In other hands,
Luchino would have been a stock mobster. Langella makes the guy seem both
peevish and dangerous. We share his frustration as things escalate and delight
in his inevitable unmasking.;    As he has demonstrated with his university
shorts and the silent feature "Sidewalk Stories," Lane is that rarity among
film makers: an amiable satirist who empathizes with all his characters. Lane
is closer in temperament to Scotland's Bill Forsyth than fellow New Yorker
Spike Lee, whose strength remains his anger. Lee's New York is colorful and
ominous; Lane's is buoyant and nurturing, a place where Audrey Hepburn could
feel perfectly at home.;    Lane spikes his first studio venture with a number
of "in" jokes and surprises -- Luchino whistles "Zip a Dee Doo Dah" from
Disney's "Song of the South"; Anthony's henchman warms up to the white Miles
and reacts to the truth like a spurned lover; James Earl Jones does a
flamboyant walk-on as theater legend James Earl Jones; veteran film maker
Melvin van Peebles appears as a cabby who lectures Miles on black power as his
fare slowly disappears under white makeup.;    Van Peebles' presence is
especially apt. In 1970, he directed "Watermelon Man," the model for this
venture. The late Godfrey Cambridge played a bigoted white businessman who
eventually learns what Miles always knows and white studio bosses will never
suspect: Black is not only beautiful but preferred.;  True Identity;
(star)(star)(star); Rated: R (for profanity, slapstick violence); Cast: Lenny
Henry, Frank Langella; Director: Charles Lane; Writer: Andy Breckman; Running
time: 98 minutes  </TEXT>
