<DESCRIPT>  FUTURE; MOVIE; VIDEO  </DESCRIPT>
<LEADPARA>  'YOU can never plan the future by the past," said Edmund Burke, the
18th-century Irish statesman.;   But Burke never foresaw the movies, or home
video, or the close relationship between the two distant technologies. In the
waning days of the 20th century, however, we all know that whatever is playing
on movie screens today will be playing in our VCRs about six months from now.  </LEADPARA>
<SECTION>  Eye  </SECTION>
<HEADLINE>  THE FUTURE OF VIDEO
WHAT WILL WE BE RENTING IN '92?
THE GREATEST MOVIE HITS OF 1991  </HEADLINE>
<MEMO>  FRONT LINES; D. Scott Apel is a San Jose free-lance writer.  </MEMO>
<TEXT>     Because the past of theatrical films is the future of video, it's even
possible to plan our prospective video rentals with some precision. While we
can't even hope to mention the hundreds of minor titles and made-for-video
tapes that will be released during the next few months, we can cover the Top
10-type titles most of us will compete to rent.;   And so, armed with nothing
more than a crystal ball (and a handful of press releases), we offer, in the
traditional Gypsy fashion, some fantastically accurate predictions about what
you'll be watching on video in the months to come.;   The crystal ball is
clearing . . . January is coming into focus . . .;   JANUARY;   "You will take
a long journey . . . ";   This is certainly true if your names are "Thelma &amp;
Louise," which will be the first major movie to hit video stores in 1992. On
Jan. 8, the two "women with weapons" begin their thought-provoking and
controversial journey to independence in this superbly written, acted and
photographed film. The following day (Jan. 9), Julia Roberts helps Campbell
Scott begin the Ultimate Journey in the romantic tragedy "Dying Young." And on
the 30th, a family of nine attempts an illegal voyage from Turkey to
Switzerland in "Journey of Hope," the 1991 Oscar winner for best
foreign-language film.;   "You will meet a tall, dark stranger . . . ";   But,
dude, it's Death himself! At least that's the sinister scene-stealer who
escorts Bill and Ted to heaven and hell in "Bill and Ted's Bogus Journey," due
on video Jan. 9. And a stranger of another kind (Wesley Snipes) awaits
Annabella Sciorra in Spike Lee's "Jungle Fever," an exploration of interracial
relationships due on video the 16th.;   "You will soon have a change in
fortune . . . ";   A true enough prediction for the incorrigible con men in
"Another You," due Jan. 8; unfortunately, this weak comedy did nothing to
change the faded cinematic fortunes of either Richard Pryor or Gene Wilder.
Ditto for Mel Brooks, playing a millionaire who loses everything in "Life
Stinks," a failed comedy about homelessness due the 29th. But the film
fortunes of teen idols Christian Slater, Richard Grieco and Patrick Dempsey
are sure to rise when their crime drama "Mobsters" hits stores on the 30th.;
"You are about to embark on an exciting adventure . . . ";   Reckless
adrenaline junkie Patrick Swayze helps undercover FBI agent Keanu Reeves
fulfill this prophecy in the action-oriented "Point Break," due Jan. 16. And
the flip-side of this dead-serious film is the no-jokes-barred slapstick
action of "Hot Shots!," a "Top Gun" parody from one of the writers of
"Airplane!," due the 30th.;   "I see the letter 'W' . . . ";   You'll also see
the letters "R" and "NC-17" connected with director Ken Russell's latest film,
"Whore," a gritty, realistic look at the oldest profession, starring Theresa
Russell and due Jan. 22. But there is a "G"-rated "W" on its way as well:
"Wild Hearts Can't Be Broken," a Disney film based on the life of a woman who
rode high-diving horses in the 1920s.;   FEBRUARY;   "An unexpected event will
change your life . . . ";   The accidental discovery of Howard Hughes'
prototype jet backpack surely changes the life of a barnstorming pilot in
Disney's high-flying period adventure "Rocketeer," due on video Feb. 5. On the
more earthbound side, Harrison Ford plays an arrogant lawyer who must re-learn
life from the beginning after he's shot during a robbery in the Mike Nichols
drama "Regarding Henry," due the 6th. And Barbara Hershey finds herself
"Defenseless" on the 26th as a lawyer in trouble, in this thriller which
co-stars Sam Shepard.;   "You will find romance -- but it is fraught with
danger . . . ";   The danger in the romantic comedy "Mystery Date," due Feb.
27, lies in the sinister figures following a nervous nerd on a date with a
beauty queen; they mistake him for his criminal older brother, and their
misdirected evil intentions cause comic complications. In a similar vein,
Martin Short is a human self-destructoid in the comedy "Pure Luck," due the
13th, an accident-prone idiot teamed up with detective Danny Glover to search
for an industrialist's missing daughter. And danger of a different brand --
the possibility of rescue and return to civilization -- plagues the innocent
teens who "Return to the Blue Lagoon" on the 5th.;   "A man of great physical
strength will take up your cause . . . ";   Jean-Claude Van Damme is up to
this challenge twice over, playing identical feet-and-fist-flailing twins out
to avenge their parents' murders in the action flick "Double Impact," due Feb.
12. And speaking of dynamic action duos, how about Mickey Rourke and Don
Johnson as outlaw bikers fighting corruption in the futuristic flick "Harley
Davidson and the Marlboro Man," due the 19th? On the comic side, Hulk Hogan
stars (with Christopher Lloyd) as a good-natured brute from outer space who
adopts a typical American family in "Suburban Commando," due Feb. 26.;   "I
sense a death in the family . . . ";   But Christina Applegate will make the
best of it -- and even learn some bittersweet lessons about life -- in the
teen comedy "Don't Tell Mom The Babysitter's Dead," due Feb. 19. On the
sinister side, there's "Body Parts," due the 20th, in which a criminal's arm,
grafted onto an upstanding citizen, continues to commit heinous crimes.;
SPRING '92;   "The images are getting hazy . . . ";   Confirmed release dates
are getting hazy, anyway. But by using the loose rule that about six months
elapses between a film's theatrical premiere and its video release, we can
predict when titles should be arriving in video stores.;   March, for
instance, ought to see the release of such dramatic entries as "Boyz N the
Hood," the critically acclaimed film about gang members, and "The Doctor," in
which arrogant surgeon William Hurt gets a taste of his own medicine when he
becomes an unwilling patient. We also should see the psychological thrillers
"Dead Again," Kenneth Branagh's Hitchcock homage; Goldie Hawn's "Deceived";
and "Shattered" with Tom Berenger and Greta Scacchi.;   And look forward to
comedies wild (the football flick "Necessary Roughness"), mild (the romantic
fantasy "Late for Dinner") and totally bizarre (the Coen brothers'
Hollywood-is-Hell allegory "Barton Fink," due March 5). Also on tap for March:
"Rambling Rose," a coming-of-age story with Laura Dern and Robert Duvall, and
"Freddy's Dead: The Final Nightmare.";   April "oughta-bes" include an excess
of execrable comedies, including John Hughes' insipid "Curly Sue";
Oscar-winning actor Joe Pesci's superfluous and superficial "The Super"; the
aptly-titled "Ernest Scared Stupid"; "Other People's Money," Danny DeVito's
disappointing comedy-drama; and -- just in time for Easter -- the coal-lump
"All I Want for Christmas." Genre titles should include Wes Craven's
tongue-in-cheek horror flick "The People Under the Stairs," and Sean Connery,
who should know better, in the sci-fi sequel "Highlander 2: The Quickening.";
 Any one of these could appear much sooner, however, following the corollary
to the "six-month" rule; namely, the worse the movie, the quicker it hits
video.;   The good news for "April maybes" is the potential video release of a
number of flawed but entertaining films, including director Terry Gilliam's
allegory "The Fisher King," with Robin Williams, Jeff Bridges and Mercedes
Ruehl; Denzel Washington and John Lithgow in the suspense thriller "Ricochet";
Don Johnson and real-life wife Melanie Griffith as a couple who learn to
communicate in the tender "Paradise"; and "House Party 2," an energetic
musical comedy.;   May might well bring us Michelle Pfeiffer and Al Pacino in
the romantic "Frankie and Johnny"; "Little Man Tate," Jodie Foster's
directorial debut; Dustin Hoffman in the gangster epic "Billy Bathgate"; and
Demi Moore in the romantic fantasy "The Butcher's Wife.";   SURPRISES;   One
more thing we can definitely predict: the release dates of small, exceptional
films are definitely unpredictable. About the best we can do is offer a
reminder to keep an eye out for such worthwhile little films as "21," in which
Patsy Kensit tells us stories of sex and seduction; "Slacker," a uniquely
structured visit with a number of engaging loonies; "Truly, Madly, Deeply," a
more adult and emotionally satisfying version of "Ghost"; Lily Tomlin's
one-woman show, "The Search for Signs of Intelligent Life in the Universe;"
the magical, musical Irish import "The Commitments"; and two art films from
director Peter Greenaway: "Drowning by the Numbers," a bizarre and comic look
at death, and "Prospero's Books," a visually stunning adaptation of
Shakespeare's "The Tempest.";   . . . AND BEYOND;   Beyond this, the crystal
ball gets cloudy. But -- lucky seers, we -- the video releases we can expect
in the summer months of 1992 just about parallel what's currently playing in
theaters. In order to divine what we'll be watching at home six months from
now, we really don't need a crystal ball at all. All we need are the movie
listings in eye-- and an eye to the future.  </TEXT>
