<HEAD>`GoodFellas' Debuts in No. 1 Spot</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserGraphic</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOHN HORN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Entertainment Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LOS ANGELES (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Director Martin Scorsese's Mafia portrait
``GoodFellas'' opened at No. 1 at the weekend box office with $6.4
million in ticket sales.
   Another mobster movie, ``State of Grace,'' on the other hand,
made $464,969 in its second weekend of limited release and finished
19th, Exhibitor Relations Co. reported Monday.
   The graphic ``GoodFellas'' stars Robert De Niro as a veteran hit
man and Ray Liotta as his shooting partner.
   The Meryl Streep-Shirley MacLaine comedy ``Postcards From the
Edge,'' adapted from Carrie Fisher's novel, finished second with
ticket sales of $6.3 million.
   In third, and soon to pass the $150 million mark, was ``Ghost,''
with $5.1 million.
   Fourth was ``Narrow Margin,'' the new thriller pairing Anne
Archer as a witness on the run and Gene Hackman as her guardian. It
made $3.6 million.
   ``Funny About Love,'' a new comedy from Gene Wilder, opened
poorly in fifth with a gate of $3 million.
   Here are the top movie ticket sales for Friday through Sunday as
tallied by Exhibitor Relations, with distributor, weekend gross,
number of theater screens, average per screen, total gross and
number of weeks in release.
   Figures are based on a combination of actual box-office receipts
and studio projections where actual figures are not immediately
available.
   1. ``GoodFellas,'' Warner Bros., $6.4 million, 1,070 screens,
$5,952 per screen, $6.4 million, one week.
   2. ``Postcards From the Edge,'' Columbia, $6.3 million, 1,322
screens, $4,784 per screen, $17.2 million, two weeks.
   3. ``Ghost,'' Paramount, $5.1 million, 1,766 screens, $2,888 per
screen, $148.4 million, 11 weeks.
   4. ``Narrow Margin,'' Tri-Star, $3.6 million, 1,132 screens,
$3,205 per screen, $3.6 million, one week.
   5. ``Funny About Love,'' Paramount, $3 million, 1,213 screens,
$2,503 per screen, $3 million, one week.
   6. ``Death Warrant,'' MGM-UA, $2.8 million, 1,090 screens,
$2,570 per screen, $9.2 million, two weeks.
   7. ``Flatliners,'' Columbia, $2.2 million, 1,469 screens, $1,490
per screen, $51.3 million, seven weeks.
   8. ``Presumed Innocent,'' Warner Bros. $2 million, 1,285
screens, $1,561 per screen, $78.6 million, nine weeks.
   9. ``Darkman,'' Universal, $1.5 million, 1,236 screens, $1,180
per screen, $30.4 million, five weeks.
   10. ``Hardware,'' Millimeter, $1.3 million, 692 screens, $1,887
per screen, $4.3 million, two weeks.
