<DESCRIPT>  RAILROAD; MOVIE; REVIEW; BRIEF  </DESCRIPT>
<LEADPARA>  Ever since the Wright brothers first launched their unpatented flying machine
from the dunes of Kitty Hawk in 1902, public interest in train travel and
trains seems to have declined considerably.;    And yet, even as an antiquated
method of moving people from one location to another since it burst upon the
travel scene with a piercing steam whistle as early as 1712, the train is
still with us.  </LEADPARA>
<SECTION>  Peninsula Extra  </SECTION>
<HEADLINE>  TAKE FANTASY TRIP RIDING KINKY RAILS OF CELLULOID
EXPRESS  </HEADLINE>
<MEMO>  Cover Story  </MEMO>
<TEXT>     Sure, a plane, car or bus might get you to your destination much quicker
than that old train, but with much less excitement, mystique and without a
certain amount of savoir faire.;    Our fascination with trains (and
subsequently with films in which trains play a major role) has not diminished
through the latter part of the 20th century. So grab your grip, watch out for
that blast of hot steam and mind your step as you climb aboard the Celluloid
Express.;    (check) Once Upon A Time In The West (1969) -- This sprawling
western, often and unfairly confused with Sergio Leone's other cinematic epic
"Once Upon A Time In America," effectively uses the train and the construction
of the transcontinental railroad as a Wild West symbol.;    The train and its
expansion across the United States portray the greed, lust, hate, love, death
and the fulfillment of dreams.;    The film's plot focuses on widow Claudia
Cardinale who is being harassed by railroad thugs into selling her late
husband's land to make way for the new rail line.;    Riddled with symbolism,
dubbed voice-overs and Ennio Morricone's thematic music, the 165-minute movie
has gathered quite a cult following over the years.;    The stellar cast
includes Charles Bronson, Jason Robards and Henry Fonda (in a marvelous
performance as one of the meanest, tobacco-spitting villains to ever grace the
cross hairs of a spaghetti western).;    (check) Runaway Train (1985) --
Although wildly uneven, this surreal cinematic train ride serves as a great
star vehicle for Jon Voight, who pulls out all the stops as a fearless escaped
convict who has the misfortune to hitch a ride on a careening, out-of-control
train.;    Many critics will point to the film as a metaphor for society's
runaway technology. Skeptics and nitpickers will point out ways Voight,
co-convict Eric Roberts and stowaway Rebecca DeMornay might have stopped the
train.;    But who cares? Train lovers, action buffs and cynics should just
sit back and enjoy the breakneck ride.;    (check) The Narrow Margin (1952) --
Forget the anemic 1990 remake of this fine, B-movie directed by the vastly
underrated Richard Fleischer.;    Tough-as-nails actor Charles McGraw stars as
the cynical detective who has the unenviable task of protecting a seemingly
ungrateful female witness on a lengthy train ride.;    Director Fleischer
makes the most of the claustrophobic interior of the train to heighten
suspenseful moments and create its own little world of film noir.;    Although
the stark action sequences are kept to a minimum, the performances are as
gritty as the stones between railroad ties and the dialogue is as sharp as a
train's whistle.;    (check)  Strangers On A Train (1951) -- Robert Walker is
a chillingly convincing psychopath in Alfred Hitchcock's classic film about
two strangers who meet quite by accident aboard a passenger train, at which
time Walker suggests they switch murders to eliminate a motive ("crisscross,
crisscross!").;    But the train in this thriller also plays an important
role. Its bass drum whistle can be heard in the background every time Walker
menaces victim Farley Granger aboard the train.;    With Hitchcock's usual
aplomb, the plot has more switchovers than the 5:15 commuter train as it comes
into Grand Central Station.;    (check)  From Russia With Love (1963) --
Although only half an hour of this two-hour James Bond film takes place on a
train, it is one of the most unforgettable and suspenseful 30 minutes of
cinema.;    Don't pay too much attention to the silly plot about British and
Russian agents trying to get their hands on a top-secret decoding machine. The
film's highlight is the incredibly brutal fight scene between good guy Bond
(Sean Connery) and villain Grant (Robert Shaw) on a train traveling between
Istanbul and the Yugoslavian border.;    (check)  The Great Train Robbery
(1979) -- Speaking of Sean Connery, he returns in Michael Crichton's terribly
polite film about the planning and execution of the theft of a gold shipment
from a moving train in 1855.;    For the most part, Crichton succeeds in
capturing the flavor of the period, aided and abetted by lavish sets and a
whimsical score.;    Joining Connery in his good-natured heist are Donald
Sutherland and Lesley-Anne Down, turning in fine performances. Director and
writer Crichton adds a nice twist at the end.;    (check)  Silver Streak
(1976) -- Much to the credit of writer Colin Higgins and director Arthur
Hiller, the story of a mild-mannered train passenger (Gene Wilder) never quite
sinks to the level of mindless violence that could have ensued.;    Indeed,
Wilder is fairly reserved as a book editor who unwittingly witnesses the
tossing of a corpse off the roof of the Silver Streak. The seductive Jill
Clayburgh is along for the ride and good-natured thief Richard Pryor turns up
to lend some timely comedy relief.  </TEXT>
