<HEAD>American Comedian Discharged From Hospital</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BRISBANE, Australia (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A hospital today discharged actor and
comedian Richard Pryor, who it had treated for a mild heart heart
attack, doctors said.
   They said he would be returning to his home in Los Angeles.
   Pryor, 49, was readmitted to the Wesley Hospital on Monday after
being discharged a day earlier. He suffered a heart attack while on
a fishing vacation in northeastern Australia last week.
   American heart specialist John Perry flew from Los Angeles
earlier this week to treat him. Dr. Perry said he recommended a
discharge after Pryor passed cardiac tests.
   Pryor was first admitted a week ago for tests after experiencing
chest pains while staying at the Sanctuary Cove resort on
Australia's Gold Coast.
   Pryor is best-known for several movies based on his stand-up
comedy performances and the comedies ``Silver Streak,'' ``See No
Evil, Hear No Evil,'' ``Critical Condition'' and ``Harlem Nights.''
   In 1980, he was burned severely and nearly died while
free-basing cocaine, which involves heating the drug over an open
flame.
   He recounted that experience and other hardships in his life in
the films ``Richard Pryor Live on the Sunset Strip'' and ``Jo Jo
Dancer, Your Life is Calling.''
   Pryor is due to start filming ``My Silent Partner'' with Gene
Wilder in May.
</TEXT>
