<LEADPARA>  'IT'S a strange irony to be making a comedy and listening to the war between
shots," says Gene Wilder, on L.A. street location with "Another You.";    He
and Richard Pryor have been making the Tri-Star picture since Sept. 4, and
Wilder also considers it an irony that the project's turning out so well after
such a bad start.  </LEADPARA>
<SECTION>  Living  </SECTION>
<HEADLINE>  PRYOR AND WILDER HAVE THE LAST LAUGH  </HEADLINE>
<MEMO>  The Grapevine  </MEMO>
<TEXT>     "Another You" is the feature on which Peter Bogdanovich was replaced as
director by Maurice Phillips after weeks of shooting. And to Wilder, the turn
of events "was like kismet -- going through such an evolution to become one of
the best things I've ever done.";    Principal production is scheduled to be
completed Jan. 29 -- after a grueling shoot that necessitated redoing four
weeks of work that had been done under the direction of Bogdanovich.;    At
this point, says Wilder, both he and Pryor are "ready to collapse." They're
talking about re-teaming -- but not for a while.;    The only definite thing
on Wilder's agenda is "to get back to my home in Connecticut and return to my
watercolor painting.";     HISTORICALLY SPEAKING: The cast of ABC's "Young
Riders" will be spending this evening at Tucson's Arizona Theater Company --
presenting "A Tribute to Martin Luther King Jr. and the Civil Rights
Movement." The program, put together by "Riders" co-star Anthony Zerbe and
theater company director Gary Gisselman, will have Don Franklin reading
excerpts from King's oratory, Stephen Baldwin reading Patrick Henry, Josh
Brolin reading Henry David Thoreau, Gregg Rainwater reading Chief Seattle --
and more. The idea, says Zerbe, is to present King in the context of "great
thinkers and speakers of history.";    Zerbe reports he and his series cohorts
expect to rush from outdoor location shooting to the theater with just a bare
hour to prepare for their 8 p.m. curtain. The idea of the tribute came up less
than three weeks ago (in the midst of much controversy over Arizona's refusal
to join the states that have made Martin Luther King's birthday a holiday).
"We knew it would be a rush, but we decided to go for it," says the actor.
They squeezed rehearsals into their off-hours.;    Zerbe insists, "This is not
a negative gesture. It's not about the state of Arizona. It's a positive
tribute to a great man.";    VIDEOLAND VIEW: Richard Dreyfuss takes on the
role of the anti-Semitic French aristocrat Lt. Col Picquart -- a key figure in
France's Alfred Dreyfus political scandal -- in HBO's "Prisoner of Honor." The
telefilm project, scheduled to go before the cameras Feb. 25, is set to be
directed by Ken Russell.;    WHAT A DIFFERENCE A YEAR MAKES: Eva Marie Saint,
who narrates and hosts the "Primary Colors . . . Story of Corita" documentary
film that's debuting this month on PBS, is saddened over how timely the
program has turned out to be. "Primary Colors" details the story of the late
Corita Kent, the nun who quit her order amid inner-church conflict over
anti-war activism in the 1960s -- and went on to gain recognition as the
pacifist artist responsible for creating such works as the "Love" stamp
design.;    The documentary was a labor of love project for Saint's husband,
Jeffrey Hayden, for more than three years. "When we finished it last year, the
cold war was over and the world situation looked bright," she says. "We'd
watch the film, see the footage of the Vietnam war protests, and think, 'How
could we have lived through all that? Look how far we've come since those
days.' Who would have ever guessed that the same kinds of scenes would be
taking place again by the time the film made it to television?" Who indeed.;
 STAR ATTRACTION: Andy Hirsch, who plays the youngest brother in NBC's "The
Fanelli Boys," says he's finally getting recognition from being on the series
-- sort of. "I recently went in for a checkup with my doctor," recalls Hirsch.
"And the nurse looked down at her chart, then up at me and said 'Do you know
you have the same name as that guy on 'The Fanelli Boys'?" Well, it's a start.  </TEXT>
