<BYLINE>By DOLORES BARCLAY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Arts Editor</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   With spring comes baseball. And what better way to celebrate
America's favorite sport than by taking home a few videos.
   Hollywood once considered baseball movies box-office poison
because movie moguls thought women, who constitute a large part of
film-goers, wouldn't want to see them and foreign audiences simply
didn't understand the mechanics.
   Before the late 1980s, studio heads may have had a point. Some
of the all-time baseball classics, though warmly embraced by fans,
did lousy box office. Such movies as 1942's ``The Pride of the
Yankees,'' starring Gary Cooper as Lou Gehrig were big
disappointments.
   However, ``The Natural,'' Robert Redford's allegorical movie in
1984 about a gifted player, and ``Bull Durham'' (1988), an amusing
and lusty tale of the minor leagues starring Kevin Costner and
Susan Sarandon, helped turn things around.
   The biggest grossing baseball movie of all time is last year's
``Field of Dreams,'' which had taken in $53.3 million by August.
``Bull Durham'' was second with $50.3 million. And the comedy
smash, ``Major League'' (1989), ran third with $48.5 million. All
three are on video.
   There are other baseball movies hard-core fans might want to
watch that will even be enjoyed by those who've never downed a hot
dog at the park.
   Here's a list of other baseball movies that are available on
video:
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
   ``College'' (1927): Buster Keaton as the unwitting jock who
tries to woe the love of his life through sports.

   ``Take Me Out to the Ballgame'' (1949): Gene Kelly, Esther
Williams and Frank Sinatra in a lackluster musical directed by
Busby Berkeley.
   ``The Jackie Robinson Story'' (1950): A poignant and hard look
at baseball's ugly history: racism. One of best biographical
baseball movies ever made, starring Jackie Robinson as himself.
   ``Damn Yankees'' (1958): Lola gets whatever Lola wants. Stars
Gwen Verdon, Ray Walston and Tab Hunter.

   ``Bang the Drum Slowly'' (1973): Excellent performances by
Michael Moriarity and Robert de Niro as two baseball buddies who
together face tragedy. ``The Bingo Long Traveling All-Stars and
Motor Kings'' (1976): A delightful romp of a group of black
baseball players touring rural America in the 1930s. Nice touches
by James Earl Jones, Billy Dee Williams and Richard Pryor.
   ``The Bad News Bears'' (1976): The first of a string of kiddie
baseball flicks. But the first is definitely the best and the
funniest. Stars Tatum O'Neal and Walter Matthau.
   ``The Bad News Bears Go to Japan'' (1978): O'Neal and Matthau
wisely dropped out.
   ``The Bad News Bears in Breaking Training'' (1977): Bad news.
   ``It's My Turn'' (1980): A limp love story starring Jill
Clayburgh and Michael Douglas.
   ``Eight Men Out'' (1988): John Sayles tough look at the 1919
Black Sox scandal with a wonderful ensemble cast.
   ``Stealing Home'' (1988): A rambling study about a talented
baseball player whose life takes a turn when he learns about the
suicide of a young woman from his past.
</TEXT>
